    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="532"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d532">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/1372</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-20">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 20, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>1104. Your 562, November 18. While waiting for full statement of facts about ship
                        <hi rend="italic">Uller</hi>, <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward
                        Grey</persName> informs me that she was not detained because of cotton
                    cargo. Cotton is not stopped by Admiralty and will not be.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
